[1] China: 5 month review H7N9, H5N6
Date: Wed 3 Feb 2016
Source: Xinhua News Agency [edited]
http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2016-02/03/c_135069168.htm


From last September [2015] to 1 Feb [2016], 44 H7N9 human cases, including 10 deaths, have been reported in the Chinese mainland, 70 cases fewer than the same period of the previous year, the National Health and Family Planning Commission said on [Tue 2 Feb 2016].

An expert with the commission said the decrease of reported cases has been related to the country's tougher supervision over live poultry markets.

Over the same period, 5 human cases of H5N6 were reported nationwide, with 2 patients dead. Official data show that as of [24 Jan 2016], China has reported 9 cases of human infection of H5N6 avian influenza virus with 5 deaths, since the 1st case was discovered in 2014.

Scientists have not found any mutation of H7N9 or H5N6 viruses that poses threats to public health so far, according to the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention (China CDC). There's no evidence of human-to-human transmission in the spread of the viruses, said Ni Daxin, deputy head of the Office of Disease Control and Emergency Response under the China CDC.

Winter and spring are the peak seasons for respiratory infectious diseases, making clusters of H7N9 and H5N6 human cases more likely in some areas on the mainland, Ni said.

